1602348205_19uAt7evT6ejhbTih1UTvPokD9KrB.body:
To anyone reading this:

If your blog is just static HTML pages, like those generated by Hugo or Jekyll, then all you need to do to make it ZeroNet-friendly is change all the links between pages on your site to relative links (like `../../index.html` instead of `/path/to/index.html`).

If your blog relies on a content management system like WordPress or a server that generates HTML from a folder of Markdown files, you will need a way to turn those into static HTML files in order to serve them on ZeroNet, as ZeroNet does not support client-server programs or languages like PHP.

I am not quite sure what this person is offering to do, as they have left neither contact information nor their Bitcoin address, but I can almost guarantee you that you will get a more satisfactory result from doing it yourself.

> [simonbellamy](#comment_15_1HwJB2bpiPPTctCtysK3198pKjMBY28vAT): Is there a CMS like Wordpress [...]

Not quite sure why you insist on using WordPress, as it's bloated when simple HTML/CSS will likely do fine. But you can run WordPress locally on your computer and then use [WP2Static](https://wp2static.com/) to convert it to a static website.

I haven't used Hugo or Jekyll, but they run locally on your computer if that's what you're looking for.
